ce:section.ce:para:
Proteinase K is one of the most effective catalysts for the enzymatic degradation of PLA [58]. Therefore, the degradation behavior of PLA-based film under the enzymatic catalysis of protease K was selected to study, and the experimental conditions were based on the results of Ref. [51]. Compared with the nonbiodegraded PLA-based films, the biodegraded films became whiter and thinner after biodegradation for 12 h (Fig. S8), and a reduction in the absorption band intensity of FTIR spectra for biodegraded films was also observed (Fig. S9). Modification of the surface morphology of PLA-based films after 6 and 12 h of degradation, in comparison to the nonbiodegraded one, is shown in Fig. 13
                        . It can be observed that the surface of the nonbiodegraded samples is very smooth (Fig. 13a, b and c). After 6 h of exposure in the protease K, small holes on the surface of pure PLA film were more and deeper, while those on the surface of MCDs/PLA films were fewer and shallower (Fig. 13d, e, and f). After 12 h of degradation, all PLA-based films were severely eroded, while the surface morphology of pure PLA film was rougher (Fig. 13g, h, and i). This indicated that the introduction of MCDs did not change the biodegradability of PLA films, but only slowed down the degradation process. The weight loss of specimens in enzyme solution was significant, in which the weight loss of pure PLA film was larger and that of MCDs/PLA film was smaller at the same degradation time (Table 2
                        ), indicating that the MCDs have a slight delaying effect on the degradation of PLA. A similar effect has been corroborated by the decrease in molecular weight (Mw) under the degradation, leading to a Mw loss of 22.04% for pure PLA film, 20.06% for DDACDs/PLA film, and 17.85% for ODACDs/PLA film (Table 3
                        ). This could be due to the fact that the degradation rate at the amorphous region might be higher than that of the crystalline region [59] and the introduction of MCD increased the crystallinity of PLA. In other words, the reduced proportion of amorphous regions in MCDs/PLA film results in a slower degradation rate than the pure PLA film. This was also confirmed by the DSC analysis (Fig. S9), which showed an increase in the crystallinity of the PLA-based films after 12 h of degradation, compared with the crystallinity of the nonbiodegraded samples shown in Fig. 9a.
